text: It is fundamental for someone offering investment advice/recommendations (whether its a talking head on tv, a Wall St strategist or analyst, someone who sells a service) to document result of recommendations. This is fundamental.

How else can a viewer or a buyer of the service evaluate the soundness/success in order to determine if there is value in the recommendations? This isnt meant as criticism, its common sense. There is nothing easier than assigning an intern to keeping tabs.
Miles wide but inches deep in analysis.

Unwatchable = "Group Stink" Comments on mortgage rates and impact on housing plain wrong -poorly reasoned exhibits no understanding of monthly payments comment nor the housing dynamic historically. Its a rate of change problem.
Yes considering rates have been artificially low for eight years. That’s a lot of pull forward

As to "move up" and sizing up from a lesser home. That is also over. Who is going to give up a 3% mortgage for a 5.5% to 6% mortgage? Turnover and activity of home sales will abruptly decline on the next small move higher in rates. @jimcramer @tomkeene

The Administration is out to lunch about denying the imminent downturn in housing. Housing is a monthly payments game - when go from 3% to 5.5%+ mortgage rates this is meaningful - comparing to past and higher rates is asinine. Refinancings down 34% year to date, a source of

consumer spend. The dual impact of streteched affordability and ++ mortgage rates is the deathknell for housing - who's activity has been pulled forward by years of artificially low rates. Autos are worse. @jimcramer @tomkeene "They know nothing."

@tomkeene $NFLX * Content Spending: Content assets increased well more than $3 billion in one quarter! One could look at content on the balance sheet like a retailer's inventory. It doesn't improve with age. Eventually it will have to go through the income statement
@tomkeene $NFLX * Foreign subs are not domestic subs: Most costs are in dollars and there is risk if the U.S. dollar strengthens. An Indian sub is not equal to one in Indiana
Kust one more thing - Lt Columbo Too many are drawing a straight line from an oversold market to a resumption of the Bull Market. Far too many. @jimcramer @tomkeene

* Content Spending: Content assets increased well more than $3 billion in one quarter! One could look at content on the balance sheet like a retailer's inventory. It doesn't improve with age. Eventually it will have to go through the income statement.

* Marketing spending: Up 39% and growing faster than sales. No scale economies so far. * Foreign subs are not domestic subs: Most costs are in dollars and there is risk if the U.S. dollar strengthens. An Indian sub is not equal to one in Indiana.
* Soaring interest expenses: Up 77% in the most recent quarter as net debt has soared to over $5 billion. Cash flow cover of gross interest is under 6x. Why use debt rather than (almost) free equity?

* Increasing competition: Disney, AT&T, Amazon (also cash flow not required). The loss of children's content from Disney should really sting. @jimcramer @andrewrsorkin @tomkeene @BeckyQuick @carlquintanilla $DIS $AMZN $T
@realmoney Netflix Talk I do not have a dog in the Netflix ($NFLX) hunt. Netflix had a terrific quarter but there are problems for anyone willing to look for some (which few are):
* Valuation: The company's market cap is now over $180 billion. This is almost at the level of Disney ($DIS) , which has 10x the cash flow. The EBITD multiple is over 100x trailing 12-month EBITD.
"Unusual call activity" (which is actually quite usual) - reported yesterday in $HD. Another one bites the dust.
@jimcramer JJ, Credit Suisse lowered $HD
Enjoy the day, all. Be independent, do your own homework and hide your children and portfolios from the self confident who, often, in reality are miles long but only inches deep.
Silliness.

@realmoney Sis Boom Nah! There seems to be an ongoing narrative today in the business media that Netflix's ($NFLX) quarterly results and the manner in which investors react to the print will be a referendum on FANG and other richly priced market sectors.

Some "talking heads" are even stating that this report will govern the direction of the S&P Index. I have to disagree. I would go one step further - its nonsensical and a detour to reality. Netflix has no resemblance fundamentally to Facebook (FB) , Amazon (AMZN) ,
Alphabet (GOOGL) or any other high beta stock. Netflix has no peer and is unique in its business profile and in the set of metrics that it is judged by.

Several "talking heads" argued that as $NFLX goes so will the markets today. I respectfully disagreed on @realmoney. The jury is out. $NFLX shares rose by +$40 or +13% $SPY is LOWER than close now $QQQ is +$0.90 or less than 0.5% $GOOGL +0.4% $AMZN +1.6% $FB flat Case closed.
